			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I've written up a good summary, lemme post it here:
<br />

<br />
Had some great fun this weekend experimenting with Heroic Opportunities.  Before I move on and explain how they work, let me start off by saying that they are ideal for good group teamwork and are ESSENTIAL for effective soloing.
<br />

<br />
Mayl took me through the steps on how to solo using HO and I look back and wonder how I ever managed to fight without using them.
<br />

<br />
Shortly after - the same day actually, I encountered a group who wanted to tackle some higher level "trainwreck" type mobs.    The group consisted of me - level 14 summoner, a level 13 scout, a level 15 cleric, a level 17 crusader, and a level 16 sorcerer.  It was a well balanced group, with a particular strength in nukeage.
<br />

<br />
We started off killing rhinos and elephants.  If you have ever taken these on you'll know they are pretty tough, with tons of hitpoints.  Now if we didn't care about HO's we could have beaten the mobs, but would have had significantly more downtime.  As it happens we had a scout who was very good and initiating HO's and keep people in line, tell people what to cast, and generally being a very helpful player.
<br />

<br />
Anyway lets get this started:
<br />

<br />
STEP 1: After the mob has been pulled and engaged by everyone - usually a good 5 to 10 seconds after this point - our scout started the first Heroic Opportunity.  To start it all players have a skill or a spell that initiates it - for me its called Arcane Augur and look at the screenshot below (f 1.0) it is represented by the man with blue flames on my spell bar.  Generally speaking scouts have the best HO's in the game, with clerics coming in a close second (or so I am told).  Scouts also have some other abilities to manipulate the actual HO - I'll get into that a bit more later.
<br />

<br />
Anyway the scout initiates his HO skill:
<br />

<br />
<img src="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000003.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
The way you can tell is the figure on the right side of the screen.  The picture of a lock and 4 symbols around it.  The Symbols represend what type of HO can be initiated by this player.  In this case we have a blue foot and horn, a gold cup, and green coin.  I have been told that each color represents a different archtype.  Gold for priest classes, blue for scout clases, green for warrior classes, and red for mage classes.  Each symbol represents a specific skill or spell type.  For example a red lightning bolt, would mean red for mage class, and lightning for a lightning type or similar DD spell.
<br />

<br />
The next spell that is cast, BY ANYONE will do one of two things: either advance the HO into the next phase, or break the chain.  For example this HO has no red.  If I were to cast a spell at this point - any spell - I would break it.  For those players who can advance the HO (either warrior, cleric or scout) the specific spells will start to blink in there own spell bar.  In this case, none are blinking for me, as I can not advance this phase of the HO.
<br />

<br />
STEP 2: In this case the scout has selected his own spell or skill (the blue horn) that has advanced it to the next round. (f 1.1)
<br />
<img src="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000004.jpg" border="0" />
<br />
The HO advances to the next step - in this example the blue horn give way to two daughter options, a red lightning bolt and a gold moon.  As stated before, anyone casting a spell that is not in sync with the HO - WILL BREAK IT. You can see the scouts warnings not to try to cast any skill or spell while he is working the HO.  Even self buffs or minor skills can stop the HO.  It does take some control and timing - obviously a cleric heal can throw the whole thing away very easily, so that why this scout has chosen a warning macro (with a few second delay to get in those last minute spells).
<br />

<br />
STEP 3: We have decided to initiate some nice direct damage spells on thie ferocous beast.  As such, I select the red lightning by casting a spell that has a red lightning symbol.  You can tell this by right clicking on any spell you have to see what symbol that uses - alternatively you can just click on any "blinking" icon when your turn comes up in the HO cycle.  In this case I have two options, my DD lightning spells and also my DD magic dust spell.  I select the dust blast spell which hits the target (resists or fizzles do not advance the HO) and move the HO to the next stage. (f 1.2) Keep in mind this step may actually take more than one spells to move it on.  At one point it took a gold cup to move it to a red flame, then finally on to the next step.
<br />

<br />
<img src="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000005.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
STEP 4: Now is where the fun really begins.  We have advanced to the Heroic Opportunity wheel.  This is where the actual HO it being created.  On the wheel you can see there are three spells that need to be cast to actually create the heroic opportunity.  This particular HO doee not require the spells to be cast in order to advance the wheel.  Some HO spells can be cast in any order, and parts of the wheel will light up when those spells are cast.  Other reqire the first spells on the wheel to be cast before the next spell can be cast.  One important note: DURING THIS TIME any spells or skill can be used by any player - it will not break the wheel.  This can be handy - especially for healers who were putting off their heals all this time.  Also there is a timelimit on the wheel (which is the blue part of the border) It's something like 30 seconds so its usually plenty of time to get your spell off.
<br />

<br />
There are usually three or more wheels per type.  In this case there are two wheels (that I know of) for the red lightning bolt.  The best part about being a scout is that he has the ability to "flip" a wheel to another HO if he wishes (but only if no one has fulfilled a spell yet).  Some  wheels are better than others, and the power to control that is key.
<br />

<br />
This wheel has three required spells - Red Star, green mask, blue horn - called Trinity Divide.  I have the first spell - red star - for me means chain lightning direct damage, which is the second icon over.  Once all the spells are cast the HO is also casted, and bonuses applied.  Some HO's give back mana, other HO's give buffs, yet others do additional damage.  In this case it was a damage add, I think this spells adds a 100-150 DD (plus all the spells that were casted in the HO to this point).
<br />

<br />
Here are some other screenshots of HO's in progress
<br />
<a href="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000006.jpg" target="_blank">http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000006.jpg</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000007.jpg" target="_blank">http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000007.jpg</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000008.jpg" target="_blank">http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000008.jpg</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000009.jpg" target="_blank">http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000009.jpg</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000011.jpg" target="_blank">http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000011.jpg</a>
<br />

<br />

<br />
Not really too difficult and fun to do.  It really gets a group working well together.  Some of the bonuses are absolutely amazing too.
<br />
Take this screenshot for example.  Pay specific mind to the damage that was given on to the last mob. (left hand chat window)
<br />
<img src="http://www.doza.biz/eq2/eq2_000010.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
At one point we became so good at doing HO we triggered a rare one that actually used 4 people in the wheel.  The direct damage that resulted was amazing.  Whatever "Past Awaking" is we had no clue, because we tried to replicate it the rest of the day and couldn't seem to do it again.[/img]</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Mendoza on Mon Nov 22, 2004 11:32 am; edited 2 times in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
